@Eric
Fools rush in, so here I come. The circled Hs and Os could be viewed as the little graphic representations of Hydrogen and Oxygen atoms, as they would be in a chemical diagram. Imagine if this molecule had, say, an atom of lead in it. (I'm no chemist, so I don't care if this is possible.) Then that little ball would be labelled Pb, neither letter appearing in the actual English word for the substance. Isn't that a traditional, i.e., non-NYT rebus?

@Steve L

As someone who’s always been a bit puzzled by the seeming appropriation of the word ‘rebus’ by the crossword community to mean something decidedly not visual (when they had ready access and ostensible appreciation of a wealth of language), I find the staunch linguistic and cultural gatekeeping of the appropriate use of an appropriated word to be utterly fascinating.

I think we should just ditch the word rebus entirely and use better words.

@Steve L
But this is a rebus.

A rebus is when something stands in for something else, like a picture of an eye for the word "I." It doesn't necessarily mean putting more than one letter into a square.

