@Billy I was wondering about DIRE as well. Merriam-Webster’s first and third definitions reflect the meaning i’ve always known (dismal, oppressive, extreme, exciting horror, etc.), but the second definition is indeed “warning of disaster.” 

However, to me anyway, that is not reflected in the example they cite: “a dire forecast.” The first and third definitions apply here, but the sense of “warning” comes from “forecast,” not “dire.” 

One does talk about the dire news, though, or perhaps a dire tarot card reading. But again, in these cases, doesn’t the sense of “presaging disaster” come from the context alone? If, for instance, you claimed your morning coffee was dire, people would just assume you’d gone to Hardee’s for breakfast, not that your mug had been brimming with bad omens.
